  _legacyStoryId: story_zombie_normal
  storySegments:
  - storyId: story_zombie_monk_seg1
    requiredItem: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 994ff2491387a4344ba6b17f3f826e0e, type: 2}
    storySummary: "The staff was less a weapon than a battered door bolt, its copper
      ring worn dull yet still warm. When it returned to his hand, the rotund zombie
      monk straightened as if tugged by an old vow\u2014still shuffling, but no longer
      aimless. Memories flickered: in the first days of the apocalypse, refugees
      crushed the temple gates, supplies ran thin, and the doors began to give. He
      cursed, \u201CDon\u2019t break my threshold,\u201D and braced the staff across
      the entrance, driving back rioters and infected, even hauling water, grain,
      and wounded like a carrying pole. Asked why he held the line, he said, \u201CMy
      vows are imperfect\u2014but this threshold, I keep pure.\u201D"
  - storyId: story_zombie_monk_seg2
    requiredItem: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 5db1e7d6b2c9e3a40a249be3055aec67, type: 2}
    storySummary: "When the prayer beads returned to the corpulent monk-zombie\u2019s
      palm, he stopped, letting out a low murmur like a sigh. His past sharpened:
      a gluttonous, hard-drinking monk by day, but each night he sat alone before
      the Buddha, turning the beads to guide souls left unrested\u2014plague-dead,
      famine-struck, and strangers no one mourned. After the world fell, he kept
      chanting for the infected, beads cutting into his wrist as he tried to send
      them on. When infection claimed him, he tried that mercy on himself\u2014yet
      the beads would not let him go."
  dialogueConversationTitle: ZombieMonk
  shortDescription: "After the apocalypse, a rumor spread through the ruins: a monk
    as round as a small hill, swaying along with sutras on his lips and the stink
    of alcohol and dried meat on his robes. Some called him a fraud; others swore
    he once saved lives. Now no longer human, he wears a faint smile and hollow eyes\u2014and
    instead of hunting the living, he only wanders, reaching for the empty space
    on his chest as if something precious is gone."
